Ed, great story, How do you think, our pot smoking, gay loving, draft dodging President felt yesterday in Texas. Here's a story you will enjoy.<br><br>
A day to honor and courage under Fire<br>
Wesley Pruden is editor in chief of The Times<br>
COLLEGE STATION, Texas<br>
 little sympathy, please, for the warrior leader of the children of the '60s. It wasn't easy being Bill Clinton Thursday in Texas. <br>
Texas, and a lot of everywhere else, turned out to dedicate the new George Bush Library and Museum here on the campus of Texas A&amp;M, where, if not the place where an appreciation of battlefield heroics was invented, is certainly the place where reverence for such things was refined. <br>
. . . . The bands played nothing but love songs to America, wearing patriotism on smartly pressed sleeves, without apology. When the U.S. Army Chorus lifted their voices on &quot;America the Beautiful,&quot; the soloist led with an unfamiliar verse that sums up what everybody here could feel, of men &quot;who more than self their country loved, and mercy more than life.&quot; If anyone in the crowd &quot;loathed the military,&quot; it was exceedingly hard to find him.<br>
. . . . Nearly everything said about Mr. Bush, from his heroics as the youngest combat pilot in the Navy in the South Pacific in World War II, to his masterful management of the allied fighting machine in the war to liberate Kuwait, seemed to draw comparisons.<br>
. . . . Some of it was not intentional. Some of it was. George Bush the younger, the popular governor of Texas, set the tone early with his opening remarks of greetings and a salute to his father. &quot;Duty, honor and country, and being always ready to serve, are the qualities that mark my father,&quot; he said. &quot;He was a president who brought dignity, honor and character to the White House, and he was a man who left with his integrity intact.&quot; Hillary joined, politely, in the applause while her husband stared unblinking into the gorgeous bright-blue autumn morning on the Texas plains. &quot;He knew first and foremost what was most important -- faith and family.&quot;<br>
. . . . The new library celebrates all those things, but there's a bold emphasis on courage under fire, duty not shirked, steadiness when the world (and sometimes just America) goes to war. The torpedo bomber that hangs suspended from the ceiling is not the one that George Bush flew over Chichi Jima in 1944. That one lies at the bottom of the Pacific. But the one here is just like it, and there's a display of a parachute, a canteen, a life raft, dye markers and a .38-caliber pistol like the stuff he carried aloft as a 19-year-old pilot. In a display case not far away, there's a letter from a Marine named Scott Seitz, permanent address unknown, written fighting man to fighting man, from the Persian Gulf: &quot;I am grateful to you for your sacrifices as the president of the United States and I am so grateful to be a citizen of the United States. I thank God I have the opportunity to serve and to know how wonderful the United States can be.&quot;<br>
. . . . Front pages of U.S. newspapers line the walls of the Persian Gulf exhibit, freezing in paper and ink the fear and suspense of six awful weeks in the winter of '91. Six of the front pages are from The Washington Times, shrieking in black boxcar headlines the growing momentum of destruction for Saddam Hussein's hollow army: &quot;Moving North.&quot; &quot;Pouring It On.&quot; And finally: &quot;We Win.&quot;<br>
. . . . The ruffles and flourishes were too much for the former president's hometown Houston Chronicle, which grumbled on its own front page that Mr. Bush was getting off too easy by his own hand: &quot;Are history books likely to overlook Bush's struggle with 'the wimp factor' just because his museum portrays him as a war hero? ... Will he be remembered as the affable family man simply because the museum has no Willie Horton, the freed convict who came to symbolize a campaign attempt to exploit a nation's racial and crime fears?&quot;<br>
. . . . It's an odd description of Willie Horton, who was a &quot;freed convict,&quot; sure enough, but who was also the brutal and unrepentant rapist who plundered a Maryland home when the little Duke, unable to look duty in the eye, put him on parole. But this media spin reflects mostly provincial misunderstanding of what presidential libraries are meant to achieve. Nobody expected LBJ to include the suspiciously overstuffed ballot box that gave him the minuscule margin that sent him to the U.S. Senate in 1948, or the Kennedy family to include reminiscences of Jack's sharing Marilyn with the mafia don Sam Giancana, and nobody should expect to see Gennifer Flowers' nightie or the bones of Hillary's cattle empire when the Clinton library opens in Little Rock a few years hence.<br>
. . . . The four presidents on hand for the dedication understood that, heaping praise on each other, and reminding each other how dependent they are on one another to engrave favorable pages in history. Jimmy Carter took pains to tell the crowd of 10,000 or so that the libraries are paid for with private donations ($40 million for the Bush library), and in his remarks, Bill Clinton, ever the fund-raiser, thanked Mr. Carter for reminding everyone how the money has to be raised.<br>
. . . . But this was an occasion for old friends to salute a man whose courage and integrity they admire. John Major, the British prime minister of the Bush years, spoke for many of them. &quot;We are here to celebrate what George Bush is, not what George Bush once was,&quot; he told the guests at a barbecue the president and his wife, Barbara, laid on on the eve of the dedication. &quot;I can tell you that we felt very safe, very secure, when he was leading the allies. We thought the principal job was in pretty good hands.&quot;<br><br>
Too bad the moonies, own the Washington Times, think I'll buy stocks in it.
